event.descr:
This trap will be generated at the start of frequency synchronization.
juniNtpSysClockFrequencyError%parm[#1]%
event.logmsg: Juniper Event: NTP Frequency Calibration Start, Error %parm[#1]%s.

event.descr:
This trap will be generated when frequency synchronization completes successfully.
juniNtpSysClockFrequencyError%parm[#1]%
event.logmsg: Juniper Event: NTP Frequency Calibration End, Error %parm[#1]%s.

event.descr: This trap indicates that some kind of time synchronization has started. This trap will be generated at the start of time synchronization with the configured time servers irrespective of whether time synchronization is done with all the configured time servers or any one of them (there may be reachability or other problems) when NTP is enabled on the router.
event.logmsg: Juniper Event: Time Synchronisation Up.

event.descr: This trap will be generated when the NTP client is not able to time synchronize with any of the configured time servers for any reasons when NTP is enabled on the router.
event.logmsg: Juniper Event: Time Synchronisation Down.

event.descr:
This trap will be generated to report the time synchronization status of each configured time server on the router when it starts time synchronization with the NTP client.
juniNtpPeerCfgIsPreferred%parm[#1]%

true(1) false(2)
event.logmsg: Juniper Event: Time Server Synchronisation Up.

event.descr:
This trap will be generated to report the time synchronization status of each configured time server on the router when it stops time synchronization with the NTP client for any reasons.
juniNtpPeerCfgIsPreferred%parm[#1]%

true(1) false(2)
event.logmsg: Juniper Event: Time Server Synchronisation Down.

event.descr:
This trap will be generated to report when the system clock offset error is set for the first time from the good time sample taken, enabling the time synchronization. This is usually the case after a system reboot.
juniNtpSysClockOffsetError%parm[#1]%

juniNtpSysClockState%parm[#2]%

neverFrequencyCalibrated(0) frequencyCalibrated(1) setToServerTime(2) frequencyCalibrationIsGoingOn(3) synchronized(4) spikeDetected(5)
event.logmsg: Juniper Event: First Time System Clock Set.

event.descr:
This trap will be generated whenever the system clock's offset error is more than 15 minutes. This is an indication that something is not set properly, since an offset of 15 minutes is not considered to be a normal offset error compared to the accuracy of the time servers and system clock. For example, it may indicate an improper setting of the timezone.
juniNtpSysClockOffsetError%parm[#1]%

juniNtpSysClockState%parm[#2]%

neverFrequencyCalibrated(0) frequencyCalibrated(1) setToServerTime(2) frequencyCalibrationIsGoingOn(3) synchronized(4) spikeDetected(5)
event.logmsg: Juniper Event: Clock Offset Limit Crossed by %parm[#1]%s.

event.descr:
This notification is generated in a dual SRP system when control transfers from one to SRP to the other in file system synchronization mode or when high availability is not operational. This notification is sent by the newly active SRP immediately following the switchover in which configuration is preserved but volatile state is lost.

juniRedundancyLastResetReason %parm[#2]%;

none(1) notKnown(2) userInitiated(3)

event.descr:
This notification is generated in a dual SRP system when control transfers from one SRP to the other and high availability is operational. This notification is sent by the newly active SRP immediately following the switchover in which configuration and volatile state are preserved.

juniRedundancyLastResetReason %parm[#2]%;

none(1) notKnown(2) userInitiated(3)
